dYAbxy2Xyhy1ZCg5W3g\",\"name\":\"Bash\",\"input\":{\"command\":\"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\\\\n  -H \\\"Content-Type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\n    \\\"scan_id\\\": \\\"0e5ab481-52cf-45a9-aeb0-f04397a63a1b\\\",\\n    \\\"project_id\\\": \\\"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\\\",\\n    \\\"scan_type\\\": \\\"observability_scout\\\",\\n    \\\"category\\\": \\\"functionality\\\",\\n    \\\"title\\\": \\\"Expose credential file gauge and cleanup metrics\\\",\\n    \\\"description\\\": \\\"The credentialInjector module tracks active credential files in a Set but never exposes the count. Add an exported getActiveCredentialFileCount() function and log the gauge at info level during sweepOrphanedCredentialFiles(). Also log when the exit handler fires with the count of files it attempted to clean and whether each unlink succeeded. This surfaces credential file leaks before they exhaust /dev/shm space.\\\",\\n    \\\"reasoning\\\": \\\"Credential files on /dev/shm are the most security-sensitive temp artifacts in the system. If cleanup fails silently (which the current catch blocks allow), credentials persist on disk indefinitely. A simple gauge metric lets operators detect the leak pattern — monotonically increasing active file count — before it becomes a security incident or disk exhaustion.\\\",\\n    \\\"effort\\\": 2,\\n    \\\"impact\\\": 6,\\n    \\\"risk\\\": 1\\n  }'\",\"description\":\"Save idea 5\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1000,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":45630,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1000},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"parent_tool_use_id\":null,\"session_id\":\"6b375ece-41c0-48fe-9151-de360e723e96\",\"uuid\":\"cd820218-7182-4450-9848-96fab187a50b\"}\n[2026-03-18T11: